# üéØ **Practical: OpenVPN Basic Setup**

## üóÇÔ∏è **Lab Details**

| Component | OS      | Role           | IP             |
| --------- | ------- | -------------- | -------------- |
| Server    | Debian  | OpenVPN Server | 192.168.80.130 |
| Client    | Windows | OpenVPN Client | Dynamic        |

---

## üìå **1Ô∏è‚É£ Install OpenVPN (Debian)**

```bash
sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install openvpn -y
sudo which openvpn   # Verify install
```

---

## ‚öôÔ∏è **2Ô∏è‚É£ Configure OpenVPN Server**

Create the config file:

```bash
sudo nano server.conf
```

‚úÖ Example content:

```
proto udp
port 1194
dev tun
auth none
cipher none
ifconfig 10.8.0.1 10.8.0.2
verb 3
```

> üîç `auth none` and `cipher none` are for lab simplicity only ‚Äî no real security!

---

## üü¢ **3Ô∏è‚É£ Run OpenVPN Server**

```bash
sudo openvpn --config server.conf
```

In another tab:

```bash
ip a
```

‚úÖ Check for **tun0** interface ‚Äî should show:

```
10.8.0.1 peer 10.8.0.2
```

---

## üíª **4Ô∏è‚É£ Windows Client Setup**

> ‚úîÔ∏è Install **OpenVPN Connect** or **OpenVPN Community Client**

Create `client.conf`:

```bash
# Open Notepad as Administrator
remote 192.168.80.130
proto udp
port 1194
dev tun
auth none
cipher none
ifconfig 10.8.0.2 10.8.0.1
verb 3
```

‚úÖ Save to:

```
C:\Program Files (x86)\OpenVPN Technologies\OpenVPN Client\core\client.conf
```

---

## ‚ñ∂Ô∏è **5Ô∏è‚É£ Start OpenVPN Client (Windows CMD)**

Open **Command Prompt as Administrator**:

```bash
cd "C:\Program Files (x86)\OpenVPN Technologies\OpenVPN Client\core"
openvpn --config client.conf
```

‚úÖ You should see:

```
Initialization Sequence Completed
```

---

## üîé **6Ô∏è‚É£ Test Tunnel**

```bash
ping 10.8.0.1
ping 192.168.80.130
```

‚úÖ Both must reply!

---

## üß© **7Ô∏è‚É£ On Debian ‚Äî Observe Packets**

Install tcpdump:

```bash
sudo apt-get install tcpdump -y
```

Check physical interface:

```bash
sudo tcpdump not port 22 -i ens33
```

Check VPN tunnel interface:

```bash
sudo tcpdump not port 22 -i tun0
```

‚úÖ **Do pings from Windows** ‚Äî you‚Äôll see ICMP packets on **tun0**, showing the VPN tunnel works!

